  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 14.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "But",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "when Jesus saw",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " it (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "ἰδὼν δὲ ὁ Ἰησοῦς",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). The Greek shows that there was no interval between the acts of the parents  and the disciples, and our Lord's seeing it. The parents were bringing the children, the disciples were rebuking them, Jesus was perceiving. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "He was much displeased",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "ἠγανάκτησε",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "); literally, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "he was moved with indignation",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". His words imply eagerness and earnestness: ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Suffer the little children to come unto me; forbid them not",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The copulative ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "καὶ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " is not to be found in the best authorities. The omission adds force and vividness to the words. The simplicity, candour, and innocence of little children are very attractive. This narrative shows with what care children should be educated. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "For of such is the kingdom",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "of God;",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " that is, of such little children as these. The kingdom of heaven belongs in a peculiar manner to little children. We know for certain that little children who have been brought to Christ in Holy Baptism, if they die before they are old enough for moral accountableness, are undoubtedly saved. They pass at once into a nearer position to the throne. \"They are without fault before the throne of God.\" Mark 10:14",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
